Mirroring and pull-through caching.

Here is a common problem at scale. Your team pulls the same base image thousands of times a day across continuous integration and production. Hitting docker hub for every one of those pulls is slow, because of latency and rate limits, and it is fragile, because a hub outage means your deploys fail. The fix is a pull-through cache, a local registry that, on a miss, fetches the image from the upstream registry and caches the result.

You run a registry in proxy mode, pointing it at the upstream and giving it a volume for storage. Then you configure your daemon to use that local cache as a registry mirror. The first pull of an image travels through the cache and stores its blobs, and every subsequent pull is served from the cache at local-network speed. The big cloud registries all support similar pull-through configurations through their own proxy modes, and for organisations doing thousands of pulls a day, this saves real money and real latency.

It is worth being clear on the vocabulary, because two related terms float around. A mirror means the cache holds the same image references as the upstream, so a name resolves the same way and the daemon simply tries the cache first and falls back to the original. A proxy is the same idea under a different name in some registries' interfaces. The daemon-side setting is the registry-mirrors option, while the cloud registries expose explicit pull-through-cache features that handle the same workflow with cloud-managed storage. Either way, the goal is the same, serve hot images locally instead of from across the internet.
